Is Bitcoin an effective long-term hedge against inflation?¶

Overview¶

The purpose of this analysis is to resolve the following questions:

1. Is Bitcoin an effective hedge against inflation?
2. How does Bitcoin compare vs investing in gold as an inflation hedge?

def concat_year_month(year,month):
    str_year = str(year)
    str_month = str(month)
    
    if len(str_month) == 1:
        str_month = "0" + str_month
        
    return str_year + "-" + str_month
In [10]:
btc_processing_df["year-month"] = btc_processing_df[['year','month']].apply(lambda df: concat_year_month(df['year'],df['month']),axis=1)

def format_year_month(yearmon):
    str_yearmon = str(yearmon)
    
    year = str_yearmon[-4:]
    month = str_yearmon[3:5]
    
    return year + "-" + month
In [43]:
cpi_raw_df['year-month'] = cpi_raw_df['Yearmon'].apply(format_year_month)

Gold is much less volatile than BTC. Particularly from the end of 2018, gold has trended steadily upwards whilst bitcoin has seen much more variance. As seen below, if you bought BTC in 2018-02 your money would only have seen an approximate increase of 1% by 2020-07, whereas gold has gone up by 38% in the same time period.

Stage 4: Conclusion¶

To answer the 2 original questions in short, I believe that:

1. Is Bitcoin an effective hedge against inflation?

No, it is not.

2. How does Bitcoin compare vs investing in gold as an inflation hedge?

Gold is a better hedge against inflation.

To elaborate on these answers, I will be referring to the charts shown in the previous section.

Is Bitcoin an effective hedge against inflation? There does not appear to be any strong correlation between the BTC price and inflation. Whilst this could have been an advantage if we saw positive price action independent of the rate of inflation, what we instead observe are significant volatile swings in the price. In 2019 when there was a sharp increase in inflation, we observe an equally sharp decline in the price of BTC. Then in 2020, when we see a decrease in inflation, we again see a sharp decline in the price of BTC.

What this suggests is that BTC is a risky investment throughout times of both high and low inflation. Whilst the volatility may be a benefit to those who can afford to hold throughout its cyclic price action, this does not make it an effective hedge against inflation, for those who are looking for a safe store.

How does Bitcoin compare vs investing in gold as an inflation hedge? Gold, by contrast to BTC, seems to have a weak positive correlation with inflation. By observing both over the last 4 years, we can see that the price of gold tends to roughly track the rate of inflation. In addition to this, as gold has much less variance in its overall price, this makes it a much more attractive option as a safe store of wealth during times of economic uncertainity. By investing money into gold during times of high inflation, you can reasonably expect the price of gold to also increase by a comparable amount.
